Function: The party meets the man Danica saved. Hemming humanizes the Black-Briar family, delivers genuine gratitude that the party hasn't earned, and offers a unique social reward. The dramatic irony ΓÇö Hemming believes the Lanterns sent Danica to save him, when in reality Davinia drove her away and Danica came here because she had nowhere else to go ΓÇö should sit in the room like a weight on Davinia's chest.
Location: Black-Briar Manor, Riften. Maven's home. The party is being invited in as guests ΓÇö not to the office, but to the family residence. That distinction matters.
Trigger: After the Maven debrief. A housecarl approaches: "Lady Maven asked me to inform you that her son would like to thank you personally. He's resting at the manor. He would be grateful if you'd consent to see him."
THE ROOM (Read Aloud)
"The housecarl leads you through the front hall of Black-Briar Manor ΓÇö polished wood floors, tapestries bearing the family crest, the quiet authority of old money. Upstairs, a corridor of closed doors. He stops at the last one, knocks softly, and opens it.
The bedroom is large and warm. A fire crackles in a stone hearth. The air smells of juniper incense and the faintly bitter undertone of healing poultices. Heavy curtains are half-drawn against the afternoon light.
Hemming Black-Briar is propped up in a four-poster bed with more pillows than seems strictly necessary. He is a man in his late forties ΓÇö Maven's sharp features softened by a different temperament. He was probably robust once. He is not robust now. His cheeks are hollow. His hands, folded on the blanket, are thin. His skin has the waxy quality of someone who was recently very, very sick and is only now remembering how to be alive.
But his eyes are clear. And when he sees you, he smiles ΓÇö not Maven's calculated warmth, not a performance. A real smile, from a man who is genuinely glad to see the people standing in his doorway."
Then improvise from: The nightstand has a glass of water, a small vial of medicine, and a pressed wildflower in a glass frame ΓÇö someone brought him flowers from the memorial. A blanket folded on the chair beside the bed suggests someone has been sleeping there. The room is tidy but lived-in. He's been here for days.
WHAT'S IN THIS ROOM
The pressed wildflower on the nightstand: What they see: A single flower in a small glass frame. If they investigate: It's from the plague memorial by the canal. Someone brought it to him ΓÇö probably Danica, probably during one of her visits to check on his recovery. He kept it. Why planted here: Connects Hemming to the memorial and to Danica personally. Small detail that humanizes.
The blanket on the chair: What they see: Someone has been sleeping beside his bed. If they investigate: Maven. She slept in that chair every night during the worst of it. The housecarl will confirm this if asked, with visible discomfort at revealing something so private about his employer. Maven would be furious if she knew they knew. Why planted here: Maven is a monster. Maven is also a mother who sat by her dying son's bed. Both things are true.
THE PEOPLE
HEMMING BLACK-BRIAR Voice: Warm, slightly raspy. He speaks carefully ΓÇö each sentence costs a little energy he doesn't have much of. Educated, mannered, but without Maven's edge. He sounds like the son of a powerful woman who chose not to become her. Body language: Tries to sit up straighter when they enter. It costs him visible effort. He waves off the housecarl's attempt to help. Pride, not vanity. Attitude: Genuine, profound gratitude. Not performed. He is a man who felt himself dying and was pulled back at the last moment by a stranger's hands. Cooperates for: Nothing. He wants nothing from them. This is the only interaction in Riften where no one is trying to leverage anyone. Pisses him off: Nothing reasonable. He is too grateful and too tired to be angry.
THE CONVERSATION
Opening:
"[He straightens against his pillows. The effort makes him cough once ΓÇö dry, controlled, the remnant of something worse. He waves it off.]"
"The Obsidian Lanterns. Please ΓÇö come in, sit. My mother told me you'd arrived. I wanted to... I needed to thank you. In person. Not through a letter or a housecarl. You deserve better than that."
On his health:
"Better. Every day a little stronger. A week ago I couldn't hold a cup. Two weeks ago I couldn't open my eyes. The healers say I'll make a full recovery, given time."
[A pause. His smile fades slightly.]
"They're being kind. I can feel what it took out of me. I'm not the man I was before this. But I'm alive, and a month ago that wasn't the expected outcome. So I will take 'alive' and be grateful for it."
On the plague:
[His expression tightens. The memory is fresh.]
"It felt like being unmade. Not from the outside ΓÇö from within. My blood turned to poison. My joints locked. Every breath felt like swallowing broken glass. And the worst part ΓÇö the absolute worst ΓÇö was when the healers tried to help and it got worse. Their magic fed it. The thing inside me ate their compassion. I watched three temple priests collapse trying to save me. They couldn't understand why their gifts were killing me."
[He looks at his hands.]
"By the end, the priests wouldn't come near me. I don't blame them. I wouldn't have come near me either."
On Danica:
"[His voice changes. Quieter. Reverent. He touches the pressed flower on the nightstand without looking at it ΓÇö an unconscious habit.]"
"And then she came."
"Your priestess. Danica. She walked into this room when everyone else had walked out. The temple priests told her it was hopeless ΓÇö that the disease weaponized their magic, that healing me would kill her. She listened to all of it. She nodded. And then she knelt beside my bed and put her hands on my chest and she..."
[He stops. Takes a breath.]
"She didn't just cast a spell. She gave something. I could feel it ΓÇö her life, her actual life, pouring into me like water into cracked earth. The sickness fought back. It tried to eat her the way it ate the others. And she just... held on. She held on and she burned brighter and the sickness screamed ΓÇö I could hear it, inside my blood, I could hear it screaming ΓÇö and then it was gone."
[He looks at the party. His eyes are wet but he doesn't wipe them.]
"She was standing when she started. She was on the floor when it was over. They had to carry her out. I'm told she aged. Physically aged. Years of her life ΓÇö gone. For me."
[A long silence.]
"I am a merchant's son. I run ledgers and negotiate grain contracts. I am not worth that sacrifice. But she made it anyway. And I will spend every day I have left trying to be worthy of the years she gave me."

THE DRAMATIC IRONY (GM Note):
Hemming believes the Lanterns sent Danica to save Riften. Maven believes this. The notice on the gate says this. The entire city believes the Obsidian Lanterns dispatched their healer to cure the plague.
The truth: Davinia slapped Danica's hands away at Korvanjund, told her to leave, and sent her into a snowstorm alone. Danica came to Riften because she had nowhere else to go. She used the Lanterns' name because it was still technically hers. She saved a city because that's who she is ΓÇö not because anyone told her to.
Every word of gratitude Hemming speaks lands on Davinia like a fist. She is being thanked for something she didn't do, by a man who is alive because of a woman she abandoned.
Do not point this out. Do not narrate it. Just let Hemming talk about Danica with tears in his eyes while Davinia sits in that chair. The player will feel it.

On the Lanterns' role:
"My mother says you're the ones who sent her. That you directed your healer to Riften when you heard about the plague. I want you to know ΓÇö that decision saved more than my life. It saved this city. There are families eating dinner tonight because you made that choice."
[If Davinia is present, he looks at her directly.]
"Lady Caelus. My mother doesn't say 'thank you.' It's not in her vocabulary. So I'll say it for both of us. Thank you. From the bottom of whatever is left of my heart. Thank you."
If anyone corrects the record ΓÇö tells Hemming that Danica came on her own, that they didn't send her:
"[He blinks. Processes. Then his expression doesn't harden ΓÇö it deepens.]"
"Then she's even braver than I thought. She came alone? Without orders? Without support?"
[He shakes his head slowly.]
"That doesn't change what I owe you. You built the company that shaped her. You gave her the name she carried into my city. She is yours, even if she came on her own. That's what good leadership creates ΓÇö people who do the right thing when no one tells them to."
[This is somehow worse for Davinia than the misplaced gratitude.]

THE GIFT
After the conversation settles, Hemming reaches for a folded letter on his nightstand. Sealed with his personal signet ΓÇö not the Black-Briar business seal, his own.
"[He holds it carefully, as if it has weight beyond its paper.]"
"My mother deals in gold and leverage. I prefer something older. Trust."
"This is a letter of introduction under my personal seal. Not the family crest ΓÇö mine. It carries a different kind of weight. My mother's name opens doors through fear. Mine opens them through... something else. Obligation. Friendship. The debts people owe me that they actually want to repay."
[He holds it out.]
"Present this to any of my family's contacts ΓÇö merchants, guild associates, political allies, people who operate in the spaces between the law ΓÇö and they will know you speak with my voice. Doors that are closed to mercenaries will open. Questions that go unanswered will be answered. It won't buy you an army. But it will buy you the thing that's harder to get than soldiers: access."
"Use it when you need it. And when you use it, they'll know that Hemming Black-Briar trusts you. That matters in places where gold doesn't."
REWARD
Item: Hemming's Letter of Introduction
A sealed letter bearing Hemming Black-Briar's personal signet.
Mechanic: Once per major city, the party can present this letter to a high-ranking NPC who operates in grey areas ΓÇö Thieves Guild contacts, corrupt officials, black market merchants, reluctant informants, closed-door power brokers. NPCs who would normally be hostile, evasive, or uncooperative.
Effect: Presenting the letter automatically shifts that NPC's disposition to Friendly for one major interaction. They will provide a critical piece of information, grant access to a restricted area, sell a rare item they'd normally reserve for insiders, or perform a favour they'd otherwise refuse.
The Cost: Every use permanently links the Lanterns to the Black-Briar criminal network in that city. It solves the immediate problem but leaves a political fingerprint. The more they use it, the more entangled they become. The letter is a gift. It is also a leash they put on themselves.
Narrative Note: This is the inverse of Maven's patron relationship. Maven's contract is explicit ΓÇö do this, get paid. Hemming's letter is social capital with no stated terms. It feels like a gift because it is one. But gifts from powerful families are never free. The party will discover this the first time someone says: "Ah, you're friends of Hemming's. Then perhaps you can help me with a small matter he and I have been discussing..."

PARTING
"[As they prepare to leave, Hemming settles back against his pillows. The conversation has tired him. But his expression is peaceful ΓÇö the look of a man who has done something he needed to do.]"
"One last thing."
[He looks at them ΓÇö all of them ΓÇö with the seriousness of someone who has recently learned what matters.]
"Watch over your priestess. Whatever she gave to save me, she cannot give again. People like her ΓÇö people willing to kneel beside a dying stranger and burn their own years to keep him breathing ΓÇö the world doesn't make many of them."
[A pause. He settles deeper into the pillows.]
"You're lucky to have her. So is Riften. So am I."
[The housecarl opens the door. The visit is over.]

GM NOTES
This scene has no mechanic, no combat, no skill check. It is pure roleplay and it should hurt. Hemming is the most sincere person the party has met in sessions. He is not manipulating them. He is not leveraging them. He is a man who almost died saying thank you to the people he thinks saved him. The fact that they didn't ΓÇö that Danica saved him despite them, not because of them ΓÇö is the knife. Don't twist it. Just let it sit in the room.
Hemming's description of Danica's sacrifice is the most detailed account the party has heard. They know it cost her "years of life." Hemming tells them what it looked like from the inside ΓÇö the sickness screaming, Danica collapsing, the priests carrying her out. If Danica rejoined the party, this is what she went through while they were in Mzinchaleft. If she didn't rejoin, this is what they lost.
The blanket on the chair is Maven's only vulnerable moment in the entire campaign. If a player notices it and asks, let the housecarl reluctantly confirm. Do not make a big deal of it. The detail speaks for itself: the most feared woman in the Rift slept in a wooden chair for a week because her son was dying. It doesn't redeem her. It complicates her. That's better.
The letter is a slow-burn reward. It won't matter tonight. It will matter in three sessions when they're in a strange city trying to get information from someone who won't talk to mercenaries. Remind them they have it. Let them decide whether the access is worth the entanglement.


